This workbook is for an introductory course in logic and discrete mathematics for computer scientists. This is based on one 14-week course with 6 chapters. The first half of the course is on propositional logic and first order logic, and the last half is on other areas of discrete mathematics for computer science such as induction, recursion, number theory, sets, relations, and program verification.
The course is cumulative and chapters rely on knowledge learned from previous chapters. The goal of this course is to give students a solid foundation in logic, proof writing, and a sampling of topics in discrete mathematics.

Every section comes with practice problems. Some chapters/sections are incomplete and will redirect back to this page. The plan is to have these chapters/sections available before they are covered in lecture. My apologies for the delay.

To report bugs, please use the brightspace discussion forum and fill out a bug report. If you have any questions, please email smcintyre at mun.ca.

